Use **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It hosts your app in-memory — no ports, no real network — and gives you an `HttpClient` wired directly to the pipeline.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add tests/MyMcp.Tests package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add tests/MyMcp.Tests package xunit
```

### Example fixture

```csharp
public class McpTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result")
                .GetProperty("protocolVersion")
                .GetString());
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts in-process |
| **Custom DI** | Override services via `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` |
| **MCP protocol** | Send JSON-RPC 2.0 POST requests; assert on `result` / `error` |
| **Session state** | Reuse the same `HttpClient` across calls (init → tools/list → tools/call) |
| **SSE / streaming** | Read `response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync()` and parse `data:` lines |

### Testing a full tool-call flow

```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task ToolCall_EndToEnd()
{
    // 1. Initialize
    await PostRpc("initialize", new { protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
        capabilities = new { }, clientInfo = new { name = "test", version = "1.0" } });

    // 2. Send initialized notification (no id)
    await PostRpc("notifications/initialized", null, isNotification: true);

    // 3. List tools
    var tools = await PostRpc("tools/list", new { });
    Assert.True(tools.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("tools")
        .GetArrayLength() > 0);

    // 4. Call a tool
    var result = await PostRpc("tools/call", new {
        name = "my-tool",
        arguments = new { input = "hello" }
    });

    Assert.False(result.GetProperty("result")
        .GetProperty("isError").GetBoolean());
}
```

Where `PostRpc` is a small helper:

```csharp
private int _nextId = 1;

private async Task<JsonElement> PostRpc(string method, object? @params,
    bool isNotification = false)
{
    var payload = new Dictionary<string, object?> {
        ["jsonrpc"] = "2.0",
        ["method"] = method,
        ["params"] = @params
    };
    if (!isNotification) payload["id"] = _nextId++;

    var resp = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", payload);
    resp.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();

    if (isNotification) return default;
    return await resp.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
}
```

This gives you full protocol coverage (init, tool calls, error handling, notifications) without leaving the process.
